data.content:
Yes! MSTest 3.7+ supports **ValueTuple-based `DynamicData`**, giving you type safety and named parameters:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string input, bool expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:**
- `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string input, bool expected)>` — compile-time type checking, no boxing
- `["valid@email.com", true]` → `("valid@email.com", true)` — tuples instead of object arrays

Also consider sealing the test class (`public sealed class ...`) for performance per MSTest best practices.
